userInput: What if I have a low income? Do I qualify for financial help?

response.stringValue: Insurance and taking care of your health can be expensive

title.stringValue: If you have, or are applying for, insurance through the Marketplace, you'll definitely want to know if you can qualify for financial help

response.stringValue:
When you apply for coverage through the Health Insurance Marketplace, you will also find out if you qualify for:

• Medicaid
• CHIP (the Children’s Health Insurance Program)
Both provide free or low-cost health coverage for some people, including low-income adults, children, pregnant women, seniors, and people with disabilities

title.stringValue: Medicaid provides insurance to more than 70 million Americans

response.stringValue: If you haven't heard of these programs before, it may be because they go by different names in some states
Use this tool from HealthCare.gov to see what Medicaid and CHIP are called in your state

title.stringValue: Click below!

response.stringValue: You can also use this tool from HealthCare.gov to find out if you qualify for Medicaid based on your income

title.stringValue: Click below!

response.stringValue: Enter your household size and state in the savings tool, and it will tell you if you qualify for Medicaid or savings on a Marketplace plan

title.stringValue: If you don't qualify based on your income alone, it's still a good idea to apply

response.stringValue: Great topic! I'm here to help 😊
Affordable Care Act plans fall under the categories of bronze, silver, gold, and platinum
Understanding these categories will allow you to pick a health insurance plan that best suits you 😊

title.stringValue: Surprisingly, these categories have nothing to do with the quality of coverage

response.stringValue: These levels refer to how you and your insurance plan split costs
